  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Postface to the Four Commentaries on the Spring and Autumn Annals
  author: Kang Hui-maeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Those who have transmitted the Spring and Autumn Annals number five schools in antiquity: the Zou, the Jia, the Zuo, the Gongyang, and the Guliang. Yet the Zou and Jia schools transmitted only through oral recitation, leaving no written texts, so their doctrines did not endure. Zuo Qiuming, having received the Classic directly from Confucius, shared the sage's sense of shame. Among the sage's disciples, the Spring and Autumn was entrusted to Zixia, and since both Gongyang Gao and Guliang Shu received the Classic from Zixia, the teachings of these several schools possess both origin and completion. In the Song dynasty, Hu Anguo, having personally witnessed the calamity of Jingkang, composed his commentary and interpretation, treating with particular rigor the principles of honoring ruler and father and punishing rebels. Thus one who reads the Spring and Autumn, taking Hu's commentary as the foundation and consulting the three earlier traditions, may finally grasp the subtle words and profound meanings by which Confucius, borrowing the records of Lu, wove into them the laws of kingship, transforming chaos into order.

    Our sovereign lord, endowed by heaven with sagely wisdom, cultivates illumination day by day. He attends the Classics Colloquium and lectures upon several texts, retiring only when night deepens. He exalts the Six Classics and widely searches the Hundred Schools, drawing the expansive into simplicity, recognizing that in the laws of all kings and the standards of ten thousand generations, nothing transcends the Spring and Autumn. Thus he commanded the scholars of the Hongmungwan to place the Four Commentaries beneath the canonical texts, arranged in chronological order. In a single opening of the book, the richness and elegance of Zuo, the discrimination and judgment of Gongyang, the clarity and grace of Guliang, and the decisiveness and rectitude of Hu appear luminously before the eye, while the sage's principles of praising virtue and condemning vice become visible, if only in the smallest measure. Glorious indeed! Now it shall be printed and widely distributed, and I have been commanded to write this postface.

    I humbly reflect that the Classic exists to illuminate principle. When principle is already illuminated, the Classic becomes unnecessary. The Commentary exists to explain the Classic. When the Classic is already understood, the Commentary may be dispensed with. Yet these Four Commentaries all serve to support the Sacred Classic, and their theories diverge. How then can we preserve all without simplification? Do we not say that the sage's brush is like the transformative work of nature itself? Those who observe yin and yang each hold their own perspective on warmth and cold, yet never stray beyond the Great Transformation. Those who discuss the sage's deletions and additions each differ in their judgments of praise and blame, yet all remain within the bounds of the sage's writing. How could we keep one and discard another? If a student investigates the commentaries to understand the Classic, and understanding the Classic comes to grasp principle, then truly the Four Commentaries become the essential path for the learner to attain principle. But should one, obscured by ignorance, cling obstinately to the Classic, neglecting the Classic while adhering rigidly to interpretation, then one cannot perceive the sovereign's subtle purpose in presenting the Four Commentaries together. How then could one presume to discourse upon that supreme guide which, beyond the historical record, transmits the way of the heart?
  footnotes:
    - The Spring and Autumn Annals (Chunqiu) is one of the Five Classics of Chinese literature. The 'Four Commentaries' (Si Zhuan) refers to the commentaries by Zuo Qiuming, Gongyang Gao, Guliang Shu, and Hu Anguo.
    - Zixia was a disciple of Confucius and is traditionally credited with transmitting the Spring and Autumn Annals to his own students.
    - The Jingkang Incident (1127) marked the fall of the Northern Song dynasty to the Jurchen Jin invasion. Hu Anguo lived through this upheaval.
    - The Hongmungwan (弘文館) was the royal library and scholarly institution of the Joseon court.
